body:
I actually encountered this case when writing several async tests that all share the same code, but where I didn't want to use `TestCaseAttribute` because I really needed the tests to be named differently. The code was similar to the following one:

``` C#
[Test]
public Task Transform_WithEmptyValue_ShouldDoNothing() {
  return TestTransformAsync("", "");
}

[Test]
public Task Transform_WithAValueTerminatedByASlash_ShouldRemoveTheSlash() {
  return TestTransformAsync("SomeString/", "SomeString");
}

public async Task TestTransformAsync(string input, string expectedOutput) {
  string output = await new Transformer().TransformAsync(input);
  Assert.AreEqual(expectedOutput, output);
}
```

Obviously this is a simplified example, the actual case had a bit more code in the "core" method, and wasn't as simple as a simple string transformation that could be implemented synchronously.

Anyway, in production code I don't really need to ask myself "Is this method implemented with async or not?" when writing asynchronous code, I just check that the method returns a `Task`. I had to dig inside NUnit source code to understand that it wasn't `Task` that was treated specially, but `async`. I think that this change can be great for consistency alone. During this process, I realized that `void` was supported too, which isn't what I was expecting at first (but is nice to have!).
